🔍 Hunting for AI Exposure Risks with KQL

As AI agents become more embedded in enterprise environments, understanding their exposure surface is no longer optional — it’s critical.

Here’s a quick KQL snippet I’ve been using to identify AI agents running on internet-facing devices:


💡 What this does:

Identifies AI agents running on internet-facing devices, including their public IPs and OS.


⚠️ Why it matters:

Exposed AI workloads can increase attack surface and risk.


🔐 Next steps:

Validate exposure, restrict access, and monitor closely.

Curious how others are tracking AI exposure in their environments — what’s your approach?



ExposureGraphEdges
| where EdgeLabel == "runs on"
    and SourceNodeLabel == "endpointAiAgent"
| join kind=inner (
    DeviceInfo
    | where IsInternetFacing == true
    | where isnotempty(PublicIP)
) on $left.TargetNodeName == $right.DeviceName
| project SourceNodeName, TargetNodeName, DeviceName, PublicIP, OSPlatform
